<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>UNIT 8: ECOLOGY, ECOSYSTEMS &amp; NATURAL RESOURCES</h1>
        <div class="subtitle">UPPCB AEE 2026 | 5-7 Questions | 20-28 Marks | Comprehensive Revision Notes (+ GATE ES Additions)</div>

        <h2>SECTION 1: ECOSYSTEM CONCEPTS</h2>
        <div class="section-intro">
            Foundation: structure (biotic + abiotic), function (energy flow, nutrient cycling), and types of ecosystems. Conceptual base for all subsequent biodiversity &amp; climate sections.
        </div>

        <h3>1.1 BASIC TERMS</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Ecology</strong> (Ernst Haeckel, 1866): study of interactions between organisms and their environment</li>
                <li><strong>Ecosystem</strong> (A.G. Tansley, 1935): functional unit of nature where biotic + abiotic components interact and exchange matter and energy</li>
                <li><strong>Biome:</strong> large regional ecosystem characterised by dominant vegetation (e.g., tropical rainforest, desert, tundra)</li>
                <li><strong>Biosphere:</strong> sum of all ecosystems on Earth — land, water, atmosphere</li>
                <li><strong>Habitat:</strong> physical place where an organism lives</li>
                <li><strong>Niche:</strong> functional role &amp; position of an organism in its ecosystem (Grinnell 1917; Elton 1927; Hutchinson n-dimensional 1957)</li>
                <li><strong>Community:</strong> all populations of different species living together in an area</li>
                <li><strong>Population:</strong> all individuals of one species in an area</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>1.2 STRUCTURE OF ECOSYSTEM</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Component</th><th>Subdivision</th><th>Examples</th></tr>
            <tr><td rowspan="3"><strong>BIOTIC</strong> (living)</td><td>Producers (autotrophs)</td><td>Green plants, algae, cyanobacteria, photosynthetic bacteria, chemosynthetic bacteria</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Consumers (heterotrophs) — Primary (herbivores), Secondary (carnivores), Tertiary (top carnivores), Omnivores, Detritivores</td><td>Cow, deer (1°); fox, snake (2°); eagle, lion (3°); humans (omnivore); earthworm, vulture (detritivore)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Decomposers (saprotrophs)</td><td>Bacteria, fungi — break down dead matter</td></tr>
            <tr><td rowspan="2"><strong>ABIOTIC</strong> (non-living)</td><td>Climatic factors</td><td>Temperature, light, rainfall, humidity, wind</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Edaphic / inorganic / organic factors</td><td>Soil, pH, nutrients (N, P, K), water, organic matter (humus, detritus)</td></tr>
        </table>

        <h3>1.3 FOOD CHAIN, FOOD WEB &amp; TROPHIC LEVELS</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <strong>Food chain:</strong> linear sequence of organisms through which energy &amp; nutrients pass.<br/>
            <strong>Two types:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Grazing food chain (GFC):</strong> starts with green plants → herbivores → carnivores; e.g., grass → grasshopper → frog → snake → hawk</li>
                <li><strong>Detritus food chain (DFC):</strong> starts with dead organic matter → decomposers/detritivores → carnivores; e.g., leaf litter → earthworm → bird; dominant in forests</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Food web:</strong> interconnected network of multiple food chains; more realistic representation; greater stability.<br/>
            <strong>Trophic levels:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>T1 — Producers (autotrophs)</li>
                <li>T2 — Primary consumers (herbivores)</li>
                <li>T3 — Secondary consumers (carnivores)</li>
                <li>T4 — Tertiary consumers (top carnivores)</li>
                <li>T5 — Decomposers (technically all levels)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>1.4 LINDEMANN'S 10% LAW (1942)</h3>
        <div class="standard">
            <strong>Only ~10% of energy at one trophic level is transferred to the next;</strong> the remaining 90% is lost as heat (respiration), used for metabolism, or remains as undigested matter.<br/>
            <strong>Implications:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Limits the number of trophic levels (rarely &gt; 4–5)</li>
                <li>Top carnivores have low population density (e.g., tiger needs ~100 km²)</li>
                <li>Vegetarian diet supports more humans on same land</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="formula">
            Ecological Efficiency = (Energy at T<sub>n+1</sub>) / (Energy at T<sub>n</sub>) × 100<br/>
            Typical value: 10% (Lindemann); range 1–25%<br/><br/>
            <strong>Example:</strong> If 10000 kcal at producer level → 1000 at herbivore → 100 at 1° carnivore → 10 at 2° carnivore.
        </div>

        <h3>1.5 ECOLOGICAL PYRAMIDS</h3>
        <div class="content">
            Graphical representation of trophic structure; introduced by <strong>Charles Elton (1927)</strong>.
        </div>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Pyramid type</th><th>Measures</th><th>Shape</th></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Pyramid of Numbers</strong></td><td>Number of individuals at each trophic level</td><td>Usually upright; INVERTED in tree ecosystem (1 tree → many insects → fewer birds → fewer parasites)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Pyramid of Biomass</strong></td><td>Standing biomass at each trophic level (g/m² or kg/ha)</td><td>Usually upright; INVERTED in aquatic (phytoplankton biomass &lt; zooplankton due to high turnover)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Pyramid of Energy</strong></td><td>Energy flow per unit time per unit area (kcal/m²/yr)</td><td><strong>ALWAYS UPRIGHT</strong> (energy is lost as heat at each level)</td></tr>
        </table>

        <h3>1.6 ECOSYSTEM PRODUCTIVITY</h3>
        <div class="formula">
            <strong>GPP (Gross Primary Productivity):</strong> total rate at which producers fix energy via photosynthesis (kcal/m²/yr or g C/m²/yr)<br/><br/>
            <strong>NPP (Net Primary Productivity):</strong> GPP − Respiration (R)<br/>
            NPP = energy available to consumers<br/><br/>
            <strong>NEP (Net Ecosystem Productivity):</strong> NPP − Heterotrophic respiration<br/><br/>
            <strong>Secondary Productivity:</strong> rate of biomass formation by consumers
        </div>
        <div class="standard">
            <strong>Productivity by ecosystem (NPP, g C/m²/yr):</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Tropical rainforest: 2200 (highest terrestrial)</li>
                <li>Estuary, swamp/marsh, algal beds: 2000+ (highest overall)</li>
                <li>Coral reef: 2500</li>
                <li>Temperate forest: 1250</li>
                <li>Cultivated land: 650</li>
                <li>Open ocean: 125 (large area, low NPP/m²; <span class="key-point">accounts for 1/3 of global NPP due to area</span>)</li>
                <li>Desert / tundra: 90 / 140</li>
            </ul>
            Total global NPP: ~120 GT C/yr (terrestrial 56 + ocean 48 + others).
        </div>

        <h3>1.7 BIOGEOCHEMICAL CYCLES</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <strong>Two types:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Gaseous cycles</strong> (atmosphere as reservoir; rapid): C, N, O, water (H₂O)</li>
                <li><strong>Sedimentary cycles</strong> (Earth's crust as reservoir; slow): P, S, Ca, K, heavy metals</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>1.7.1 CARBON CYCLE</h3>
        <div class="formula">
            <strong>Pools (reservoirs):</strong><br/>
            • Atmosphere: ~830 GtC (425 ppm CO₂, 2024)<br/>
            • Oceans: ~38000 GtC (largest active pool)<br/>
            • Soils: ~1500 GtC<br/>
            • Vegetation: ~550 GtC<br/>
            • Fossil fuels: ~5000 GtC (recoverable)<br/>
            • Sedimentary rocks (limestone): ~10⁸ GtC (locked, slow)<br/><br/>
            <strong>Major fluxes:</strong><br/>
            • Photosynthesis: ~120 GtC/yr (terrestrial)<br/>
            • Respiration + decomposition: ~119 GtC/yr<br/>
            • Anthropogenic emission: ~10 GtC/yr (≈ 36 GtCO₂)<br/>
            • Ocean uptake: ~2.5 GtC/yr; Land sink: ~3 GtC/yr<br/>
            • Atmospheric increase: ~5 GtC/yr (residual)
        </div>

        <h3>1.7.2 NITROGEN CYCLE</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <strong>5 key processes:</strong>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>N-fixation:</strong> N₂ → NH₃; biological by <em>Rhizobium</em> (legumes), <em>Azotobacter</em> (free), <em>Azolla-Anabaena</em> (paddy), cyanobacteria; abiotic by lightning (~5%) &amp; industrial Haber-Bosch</li>
                <li><strong>Ammonification:</strong> organic N → NH₄⁺ by decomposers</li>
                <li><strong>Nitrification:</strong> NH₄⁺ → NO₂⁻ (Nitrosomonas) → NO₃⁻ (Nitrobacter); aerobic; releases H⁺ (acidifies soil)</li>
                <li><strong>Assimilation:</strong> uptake of NO₃⁻/NH₄⁺ by plants</li>
                <li><strong>Denitrification:</strong> NO₃⁻ → N₂ by <em>Pseudomonas</em>, <em>Bacillus</em>; anaerobic; closes the cycle; produces N₂O (potent GHG, GWP 273)</li>
            </ol>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight">
            <strong>Anthropogenic N inputs:</strong> Haber-Bosch (~120 Tg N/yr) now exceeds natural BNF (~110 Tg N/yr); causing eutrophication, acid rain, GHG; "the great nitrogen problem".
        </div>

        <h3>1.7.3 PHOSPHORUS CYCLE</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <ul>
                <li>No gaseous phase (no atmospheric reservoir)</li>
                <li>Cycles via weathering of rocks → soil → plants → animals → decomposition → soil/sediment</li>
                <li>Main reservoir: phosphate rock (apatite); reaches ocean via runoff &amp; rivers</li>
                <li>Main human disruption: fertiliser use, detergents → eutrophication</li>
                <li>Slowest of the major cycles; "peak phosphorus" concern (Morocco holds ~70% of reserves)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>1.7.4 SULPHUR CYCLE</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <ul>
                <li>Reservoirs: sulphate (SO₄²⁻) in seawater (largest), sediments, atmosphere</li>
                <li>Volcanic SO₂, biogenic DMS (dimethyl sulphide from oceans)</li>
                <li>Anthropogenic: combustion of S-bearing fuels → SO₂ → H₂SO₄ → acid rain</li>
                <li>Sulphate-reducing bacteria (anaerobic) produce H₂S in waterlogged soils, sediments</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>1.7.5 WATER (HYDROLOGICAL) CYCLE</h3>
        <div class="content">
            Evaporation + transpiration → atmospheric water vapour → condensation → precipitation → surface runoff + infiltration + groundwater → rivers → ocean. Key drivers: solar energy + gravity. Global precipitation ≈ global evapotranspiration = ~5×10⁵ km³/yr.
        </div>

        <div class="gate-add">
            <strong>GATE ADD — Role of microorganisms in biogeochemical cycling:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>N-fixers:</strong> Rhizobium, Azotobacter, Azospirillum, Frankia, Anabaena, Nostoc</li>
                <li><strong>Nitrifiers:</strong> Nitrosomonas, Nitrosococcus (NH₄⁺ → NO₂⁻); Nitrobacter, Nitrospira (NO₂⁻ → NO₃⁻)</li>
                <li><strong>Denitrifiers:</strong> Pseudomonas, Bacillus, Paracoccus</li>
                <li><strong>Sulphate-reducers:</strong> Desulfovibrio (anaerobic; H₂S production)</li>
                <li><strong>Sulphur-oxidisers:</strong> Thiobacillus (H₂S → SO₄²⁻; aerobic)</li>
                <li><strong>P-solubilisers:</strong> Bacillus megaterium, Pseudomonas striata, Aspergillus, Penicillium (release immobile P)</li>
                <li><strong>Methanogens:</strong> archaea; CO₂/H₂ + acetate → CH₄ in anaerobic environments (paddy, landfills, gut)</li>
                <li><strong>Methanotrophs:</strong> Methylococcus, Methylosinus oxidise CH₄ → CO₂ (control GHG)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>SECTION 2: TYPES OF ECOSYSTEMS</h2>
        <div class="section-intro">
            Major ecosystems &amp; their characteristics. GATE ADD has detailed coverage of wetlands, forests, coastal, aquatic.
        </div>

        <h3>2.1 TERRESTRIAL ECOSYSTEMS</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Biome</th><th>Climate</th><th>Vegetation</th><th>Indian example</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Tropical rainforest</td><td>Hot, &gt; 2000 mm rain, no dry season</td><td>Multi-storied evergreen, lianas, epiphytes; high biodiversity</td><td>Western Ghats, NE India, A&amp;N</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Tropical deciduous</td><td>Hot; 1000–2000 mm; dry season</td><td>Sal, teak; leaves shed in dry season</td><td>Central India</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Savanna / Grassland</td><td>Warm; 500–1500 mm; long dry</td><td>Grasses + scattered trees</td><td>Banni grasslands (Kutch); Terai</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Desert</td><td>&lt; 250 mm rain; high T variation</td><td>Cacti, succulents, xerophytes</td><td>Thar (Rajasthan); Cold desert (Ladakh)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Temperate forest</td><td>Moderate T; 750–1500 mm</td><td>Oak, maple, deciduous</td><td>Himalayan mid-elevations</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Coniferous (Taiga)</td><td>Cold; long winter</td><td>Pine, spruce, fir</td><td>Higher Himalayas</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Tundra (alpine)</td><td>Very cold; permafrost</td><td>Lichens, mosses, dwarf shrubs</td><td>Above tree line in Himalayas</td></tr>
        </table>

        <h3>2.2 FOREST ECOSYSTEM <span style="color:#673ab7;">(GATE ADD detail)</span></h3>
        <div class="content">
            <strong>India forest cover (ISFR 2023, FSI Dehradun):</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Total forest cover: <strong>7,15,343 km² (21.76% of geographical area)</strong></li>
                <li>Tree cover (outside forest): 1,12,014 km² (3.41%)</li>
                <li>Total forest + tree cover: 8,27,357 km² (25.17%)</li>
                <li>Largest forest cover state: <strong>Madhya Pradesh</strong> (77,073 km²)</li>
                <li>Highest % forest cover: <strong>Mizoram</strong> (84.53%)</li>
                <li>Mangrove cover: 4992 km² (largest in West Bengal — Sundarbans)</li>
                <li><strong>National Forest Policy 1988</strong> target: 33% forest &amp; tree cover</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Forest classification (Champion &amp; Seth, 1968):</strong> 16 major types — tropical wet evergreen, tropical semi-evergreen, tropical moist deciduous, littoral &amp; swamp, tropical dry deciduous, tropical thorn, tropical dry evergreen, subtropical broadleaved hill, subtropical pine, subtropical dry evergreen, montane wet temperate, Himalayan moist temperate, Himalayan dry temperate, sub-alpine, moist alpine scrub, dry alpine scrub.
        </div>

        <h3>2.3 AQUATIC ECOSYSTEMS</h3>
        <div class="standard">
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Freshwater:</strong> lentic (lakes, ponds — still); lotic (rivers, streams — flowing)</li>
                <li><strong>Marine:</strong> oceans (97% of Earth's water); estuaries (river mouth, brackish); coral reefs; mangroves; coastal zones</li>
                <li><strong>Wetlands</strong> (transitional): swamps, marshes, bogs, peatlands</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Lake stratification (in temperate lakes):</strong> 3 layers in summer:
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Epilimnion</strong> — warm, well-mixed, aerobic upper layer</li>
                <li><strong>Thermocline / Metalimnion</strong> — sharp T gradient (~1°C/m)</li>
                <li><strong>Hypolimnion</strong> — cold, dense, often anaerobic bottom</li>
            </ol>
            Spring &amp; autumn turnover mix the layers, redistributing O₂ and nutrients. Tropical lakes (mostly polymictic) are less strongly stratified.
        </div>

        <h3>2.4 WETLAND ECOSYSTEM <span style="color:#673ab7;">(GATE ADD)</span></h3>
        <div class="content">
            <strong>Wetland</strong> = land transitional between terrestrial &amp; aquatic systems, where water table is at/near surface or land is covered by shallow water (Ramsar definition).
            <ul>
                <li>Highly productive (NPP 2000+ g C/m²/yr)</li>
                <li>Functions: flood control, water purification, groundwater recharge, carbon sequestration, biodiversity habitat, fisheries</li>
                <li>India: <strong>85 Ramsar sites</strong> (2024); largest network in South Asia</li>
                <li><strong>Sundarbans</strong> (West Bengal) — largest Ramsar site in India</li>
                <li>Wetland Rules 2017 — Wetland Authority at state level; prohibited activities (encroachment, untreated discharge, solid waste disposal)</li>
                <li>Threats: drainage for agriculture/urbanisation; pollution; eutrophication; invasive species (water hyacinth, salvinia)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>2.5 COASTAL &amp; MARINE ECOSYSTEMS <span style="color:#673ab7;">(GATE ADD)</span></h3>
        <div class="content">
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Estuaries:</strong> brackish; very productive; nursery for many species</li>
                <li><strong>Mangroves:</strong> halophytic trees; pneumatophores for breathing; viviparous; protect coast from cyclones &amp; tsunamis; carbon sequestration ("blue carbon")</li>
                <li><strong>Coral reefs:</strong> formed by coral polyps + symbiotic <em>zooxanthellae</em> (dinoflagellates); occupy &lt; 1% of ocean but house ~25% of marine species; threatened by bleaching (rising T &gt; 30°C, acidification pH &lt; 8.0)</li>
                <li><strong>Seagrasses:</strong> flowering plants in marine; carbon sequestration</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>India coast:</strong> 7517 km coastline; 12 major ports; CRZ regulations applicable.<br/>
            <strong>Indian coral reefs:</strong> Gulf of Mannar, Gulf of Kachchh, Lakshadweep, Andaman &amp; Nicobar.<br/>
            <strong>Indian mangroves:</strong> 4992 km²; Sundarbans (largest), Bhitarkanika (Odisha), Pichavaram, Mahanadi, Krishna-Godavari.
        </div>

        <h3>2.6 ECOLOGICAL SUCCESSION</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <strong>Definition:</strong> orderly process of community change over time leading to a stable climax community.<br/>
            <strong>Two types:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Primary succession:</strong> on a previously uncolonised area (bare rock, lava, sand dunes); pioneer = lichens; takes centuries to millennia</li>
                <li><strong>Secondary succession:</strong> on disturbed area where soil exists (after fire, abandoned farm); faster (decades)</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Stages (sere):</strong> Pioneer → Intermediate → Climax<br/>
            <strong>Hydrosere:</strong> succession in water (phytoplankton → submerged → floating → reed swamp → marsh → forest)<br/>
            <strong>Xerosere:</strong> succession in dry conditions (lichens → mosses → grasses → shrubs → trees)
        </div>

        <h2>SECTION 3: BIODIVERSITY</h2>
        <div class="section-intro">
            Levels, hot spots, conservation. High recall — multiple Qs guaranteed.
        </div>

        <h3>3.1 LEVELS OF BIODIVERSITY</h3>
        <div class="standard">
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Genetic diversity:</strong> variation within a species (different breeds, cultivars, strains)</li>
                <li><strong>Species diversity:</strong> variety of species in a region</li>
                <li><strong>Ecosystem diversity:</strong> variety of habitats/communities</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Whittaker's spatial scales:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Alpha (α) diversity:</strong> within a single habitat / community</li>
                <li><strong>Beta (β) diversity:</strong> between habitats / along environmental gradient</li>
                <li><strong>Gamma (γ) diversity:</strong> total at landscape / regional level</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="formula">
            <strong>Shannon-Wiener Index (H):</strong>  H = − Σ p<sub>i</sub> · ln(p<sub>i</sub>)<br/>
            p<sub>i</sub> = proportion of species i; higher H = more diverse<br/><br/>
            <strong>Simpson's Index (D):</strong>  D = Σ p<sub>i</sub>²<br/>
            Range 0–1; lower D = more diverse; sometimes reported as 1 − D
        </div>

        <h3>3.2 GLOBAL BIODIVERSITY HOTSPOTS</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <strong>Concept by Norman Myers (1988, refined 2000).</strong> Two criteria for hotspot:
            <ol>
                <li>Must contain ≥ <strong>1500 endemic vascular plant species</strong> (≥ 0.5% of world's total)</li>
                <li>Must have lost ≥ <strong>70% of original primary vegetation</strong></li>
            </ol>
            <strong>36 hotspots globally</strong> (as of 2024 — Forests of East Australia added).<br/>
            <strong>4 hotspots in India (cover parts of):</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Western Ghats &amp; Sri Lanka</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Himalaya</strong> (entire arc — Eastern + Central)</li>
                <li><strong>Indo-Burma</strong> (NE India + parts of Bangladesh, Myanmar, Thailand, Vietnam, etc.)</li>
                <li><strong>Sundaland</strong> (covers Nicobar Islands part of India)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>3.3 IUCN RED LIST CATEGORIES (2001 system)</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Category</th><th>Code</th><th>Definition</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Extinct</td><td>EX</td><td>No living individual</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Extinct in the Wild</td><td>EW</td><td>Survives only in captivity</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Critically Endangered</strong></td><td>CR</td><td>Extremely high risk of extinction in wild</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Endangered</td><td>EN</td><td>High risk of extinction</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Vulnerable</td><td>VU</td><td>Faces high risk in medium term</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Near Threatened</td><td>NT</td><td>Close to qualifying for VU</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Least Concern</td><td>LC</td><td>Widespread, abundant</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Data Deficient</td><td>DD</td><td>Inadequate information</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Not Evaluated</td><td>NE</td><td>Not yet assessed</td></tr>
        </table>
        <div class="highlight">
            <strong>Threatened categories:</strong> CR + EN + VU. Indian examples — CR: Great Indian Bustard, Pygmy Hog, Gharial, Hangul; EN: Tiger, Asiatic Lion, Snow Leopard, Indian Elephant; VU: Sloth Bear, Blackbuck.
        </div>

        <h3>3.4 BIODIVERSITY CONSERVATION — IN-SITU vs EX-SITU</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>In-situ (on-site)</th><th>Ex-situ (off-site)</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Concept</td><td>Conserve in natural habitat</td><td>Conserve outside natural habitat</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Examples</td><td>National Parks, Wildlife Sanctuaries, Biosphere Reserves, Conservation Reserves, Sacred Groves, Ramsar sites</td><td>Zoos, botanical gardens, gene banks, seed banks, cryopreservation, tissue culture, captive breeding centres</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Indian examples</td><td>106 NPs; 573 WLS; 18 BRs; 55 Tiger Reserves; 33 Elephant Reserves</td><td>NBPGR (Delhi), CCMB (Hyderabad — LaCONES), CICR (Nagpur), FRI (Dehradun), ~150 zoos under CZA</td></tr>
        </table>

        <h3>3.5 BIOSPHERE RESERVES (BRs)</h3>
        <div class="standard">
            <strong>UNESCO MAB programme (1971);</strong> India started declaring 1986. 18 BRs in India; <strong>12 are part of UNESCO World Network</strong>.
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Three zones:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Core zone:</strong> legally protected, no human activity, undisturbed</li>
                        <li><strong>Buffer zone:</strong> limited human activity (research, education, tourism)</li>
                        <li><strong>Transition zone:</strong> human settlements, sustainable use</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>First BR in India:</strong> Nilgiri (1986); UNESCO listed 2000</li>
                <li><strong>Largest:</strong> Gulf of Mannar (10,500 km²)</li>
                <li>Recent additions to UNESCO list: Panna (2020)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>3.6 PROJECT TIGER &amp; OTHER SPECIES PROGRAMMES</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Project Tiger</strong> (1973, India + WWF + IUCN); <strong>NTCA</strong> statutory body since 2006; <strong>55 tiger reserves</strong> covering ~75,000 km²; tiger population: ~3682 (2022 census)</li>
            <li><strong>Project Elephant</strong> (1992); <strong>33 elephant reserves</strong>; ~30,000 elephants in India</li>
            <li><strong>Project Snow Leopard</strong> (2009); ~700 in India</li>
            <li><strong>Project Crocodile</strong> (1975) — gharial recovery</li>
            <li><strong>Project Hangul</strong> (Kashmir stag, J&amp;K)</li>
            <li><strong>Project Dolphin</strong> (2020) — Ganges &amp; Indus river dolphin (national aquatic animal since 2009)</li>
            <li><strong>Project Cheetah</strong> (2022) — reintroduction at Kuno NP, MP from Namibia/South Africa</li>
            <li><strong>Vulture Recovery Programme</strong> — captive breeding (Pinjore Haryana); diclofenac ban</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>3.7 INVASIVE ALIEN SPECIES (IAS)</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <strong>IAS:</strong> non-native species that establish &amp; spread, causing economic / environmental harm.<br/>
            <strong>Examples in India:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Plants:</strong> <em>Lantana camara</em>, <em>Parthenium hysterophorus</em> (congress grass), <em>Eichhornia crassipes</em> (water hyacinth), <em>Prosopis juliflora</em> (vilayati kikar), <em>Mikania micrantha</em>, <em>Mimosa diplotricha</em></li>
                <li><strong>Animals:</strong> African catfish, common carp, suckermouth catfish, giant African snail, red-eared slider</li>
            </ul>
            IAS = <strong>2nd largest cause of biodiversity loss globally</strong> (after habitat destruction).
        </div>

        <h2>SECTION 4: CLIMATE CHANGE &amp; GLOBAL ISSUES</h2>

        <h3>4.1 ENHANCED GREENHOUSE EFFECT</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <strong>Natural greenhouse effect:</strong> earth's avg surface temperature would be ~ −18°C without GHGs; actual ~15°C (33°C warming due to natural GHG).<br/>
            <strong>Enhanced greenhouse effect:</strong> additional warming from anthropogenic GHGs (CO₂, CH₄, N₂O, F-gases).<br/>
            <strong>Global temperature rise (IPCC AR6, 2021):</strong> +1.1°C above pre-industrial baseline (1850-1900); +1.5°C threshold likely breached in 2030s without rapid action.
        </div>

        <h3>4.2 IPCC AR6 KEY FINDINGS (2021–22)</h3>
        <div class="standard">
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Working Group I (Physical Science):</strong> Aug 2021 — "unequivocal that human influence has warmed atmosphere, ocean and land"</li>
                <li><strong>Working Group II (Impacts):</strong> Feb 2022 — adaptation gaps, climate justice</li>
                <li><strong>Working Group III (Mitigation):</strong> Apr 2022 — peak emissions before 2025; halve by 2030 for 1.5°C</li>
                <li><strong>Synthesis Report:</strong> March 2023 — narrowing window for action</li>
                <li>Global mean sea level: rose 0.20 m (1901–2018); accelerating</li>
                <li>Arctic sea ice: declining 13% per decade</li>
                <li>Increasing frequency &amp; intensity of extreme events: heatwaves, cyclones, floods, droughts</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Carbon budget:</strong> ~500 GtCO₂ remaining (50% chance) for 1.5°C from 2020 onwards. At 40 GtCO₂/yr, exhausted by 2032.
        </div>

        <h3>4.3 CLIMATE CHANGE — INDIA SPECIFIC</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <ul>
                <li>India is 3rd largest GHG emitter (~7% of global); per capita ~1.9 t CO₂/yr (well below world avg 4.7)</li>
                <li><strong>India's Updated NDC (Aug 2022):</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Reduce emissions intensity of GDP by <strong>45%</strong> by 2030 (from 2005)</li>
                        <li>Achieve <strong>50% cumulative installed capacity from non-fossil</strong> by 2030</li>
                        <li>Create additional carbon sink of <strong>2.5–3 BT CO₂eq</strong> by 2030 (forests/tree cover)</li>
                        <li><strong>Net-zero by 2070</strong> (Glasgow COP26 announcement, Nov 2021)</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Panchamrit pledges (COP26, Nov 2021):</strong>
                    <ol>
                        <li>500 GW non-fossil installed capacity by 2030</li>
                        <li>50% of energy from RE by 2030</li>
                        <li>Reduce 1 BT CO₂ from total projected emissions by 2030</li>
                        <li>Reduce carbon intensity of economy by 45% by 2030</li>
                        <li>Net-zero by 2070</li>
                    </ol>
                </li>
                <li><strong>NAPCC 2008</strong> — 8 missions (see Unit 6)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>4.4 ADAPTATION vs MITIGATION</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Mitigation</th><th>Adaptation</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Goal</td><td>Reduce / prevent emission of GHGs</td><td>Adjust to actual / expected climate impacts</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Examples</td><td>Renewable energy; energy efficiency; afforestation; carbon capture; EV; methane reduction</td><td>Drought-resistant crops; sea wall; cyclone shelters; early warning systems; insurance; water conservation</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Timeframe</td><td>Long-term, global benefit</td><td>Short-medium term, local benefit</td></tr>
            <tr><td>India's approach</td><td>NAPCC (8 missions); EVs; solar push</td><td>National Adaptation Fund (NAFCC) ₹350 cr</td></tr>
        </table>

        <h3>4.5 CARBON SEQUESTRATION</h3>
        <div class="content">
            Process of capturing &amp; storing atmospheric CO₂.
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Biological:</strong> forests (afforestation, reforestation), soils (regenerative agriculture), oceans</li>
                <li><strong>Blue carbon:</strong> mangroves (10× C storage of terrestrial forests), seagrasses, salt marshes — high but threatened</li>
                <li><strong>Geological:</strong> CCS (Carbon Capture &amp; Storage) — CO₂ injected into depleted oil/gas fields, saline aquifers, basalts</li>
                <li><strong>Mineral carbonation:</strong> CO₂ + Mg/Ca silicates → carbonates (permanent)</li>
                <li><strong>BECCS (Bioenergy with CCS):</strong> negative emissions technology</li>
                <li><strong>Direct Air Capture (DAC):</strong> Climeworks plants (Iceland Orca/Mammoth)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="gate-add">
            <strong>GATE ADD — Other global effects:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Urban Heat Island:</strong> cities 2–8°C warmer; concrete/asphalt; reduced vegetation; anthropogenic heat. Mitigation: green roofs, cool pavements, urban forests, water bodies</li>
                <li><strong>Stratospheric ozone hole:</strong> Antarctic ozone "hole" discovered 1985 (Farman); polar stratospheric clouds + ClO chemistry; expected to close by 2065 (Montreal Protocol success)</li>
                <li><strong>Ocean acidification:</strong> CO₂ + H₂O → H₂CO₃; ocean pH dropped from 8.2 to 8.1 (~30% increase in [H⁺]); harms calcifying organisms (corals, molluscs)</li>
                <li><strong>Permafrost thaw:</strong> releases CH₄ from previously frozen tundra (positive feedback)</li>
                <li><strong>Albedo feedback:</strong> melting ice → less reflection → more warming (positive feedback)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>4.6 SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT GOALS (SDGs) <span style="color:#673ab7;">(GATE ADD)</span></h3>
        <div class="standard">
            UN 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development; <strong>17 SDGs, 169 targets, 232 indicators;</strong> adopted 25 September 2015; replaced MDGs.
            <ul>
                <li>1: No poverty | 2: Zero hunger | 3: Good health | 4: Quality education | 5: Gender equality</li>
                <li>6: Clean water &amp; sanitation | 7: Affordable &amp; clean energy | 8: Decent work | 9: Industry, innovation, infrastructure | 10: Reduced inequalities</li>
                <li>11: Sustainable cities &amp; communities | 12: Responsible consumption &amp; production | 13: Climate action | 14: Life below water | 15: Life on land</li>
                <li>16: Peace, justice &amp; strong institutions | 17: Partnerships for the goals</li>
            </ul>
            India: Niti Aayog publishes annual SDG India Index; 2023-24 score 71/100.
        </div>

        <h3>4.7 SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT — CONCEPT &amp; HURDLES <span style="color:#673ab7;">(GATE ADD)</span></h3>
        <div class="content">
            <strong>Definition (Brundtland 1987):</strong> "development that meets the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs".<br/>
            <strong>Three pillars:</strong> economic + social + environmental ("triple bottom line").<br/>
            <strong>Hurdles to sustainability:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Population growth (currently ~8.1 billion; projected 9.7 by 2050)</li>
                <li>Over-consumption in developed nations</li>
                <li>Inequitable resource distribution</li>
                <li>Short-term political &amp; economic decisions; "tragedy of the commons" (Hardin 1968)</li>
                <li>Externalities not priced in markets (pollution, biodiversity loss)</li>
                <li>Technology lock-in (fossil fuel infrastructure)</li>
                <li>Lack of international cooperation; geopolitical tensions</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Environment-economics nexus:</strong> Environmental Kuznets Curve hypothesis — pollution rises with income then declines past inflection point (debated empirically).
        </div>

        <h2>SECTION 5: NATURAL RESOURCES</h2>

        <h3>5.1 CLASSIFICATION</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Renewable resources:</strong> regenerate naturally within a human timescale (solar, wind, hydro, biomass, geothermal, tidal; forests, fisheries, soil — if managed sustainably)</li>
                <li><strong>Non-renewable resources:</strong> finite stock; deplete with use (fossil fuels, minerals, fossil aquifers)</li>
                <li><strong>Inexhaustible:</strong> solar, wind (essentially unlimited)</li>
                <li><strong>Stock vs flow resources;</strong> reserves vs resources distinction</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>5.2 FOREST RESOURCES — INDIA</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <ul>
                <li>Forest cover: 7,15,343 km² = 21.76% (ISFR 2023); target 33% (NFP 1988)</li>
                <li>Annual loss: ~1500 km²/yr (mostly to mining, infrastructure, encroachment)</li>
                <li>Causes of deforestation: shifting cultivation (jhum), commercial logging, infrastructure (roads, dams), mining, fires (esp. Uttarakhand summer), encroachment</li>
                <li><strong>Effects:</strong> biodiversity loss, soil erosion, hydrological disruption, climate change (15–17% of global CO₂ from deforestation), loss of livelihoods of forest-dependent communities</li>
                <li><strong>Conservation programs:</strong> Joint Forest Management (JFM, 1990); CAMPA (CAF Act 2016); Green India Mission (NAPCC)</li>
                <li><strong>Forest Rights Act 2006</strong> — recognises rights of forest-dwelling communities</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>5.3 WATER RESOURCES</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <ul>
                <li>India has 4% of world's freshwater &amp; 18% of population</li>
                <li>Per capita availability: declining from 5177 m³/yr (1951) → 1486 m³/yr (2021); &lt; 1700 = water stressed; &lt; 1000 = water scarce</li>
                <li>Sectoral use: <strong>agriculture 78–80%</strong>, domestic 6–7%, industry 5–6%, others</li>
                <li><strong>Groundwater over-exploitation:</strong> CGWB (Central Ground Water Board) classifies blocks as Safe / Semi-Critical / Critical / Over-Exploited (&gt; 100% of recharge extracted)</li>
                <li>~17% of blocks Over-Exploited (mostly Punjab, Haryana, Rajasthan, Gujarat, TN)</li>
                <li><strong>CGWA</strong> (Central Ground Water Authority) — regulator under E(P) Act 1986; permission needed for industrial extraction in OE/critical areas</li>
                <li>Major schemes: Jal Jeevan Mission (2019, har ghar nal se jal); Atal Bhujal Yojana (2020); Jal Shakti Abhiyan</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>5.4 SOIL RESOURCES</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <strong>Soil erosion types:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Sheet erosion:</strong> uniform removal of topsoil; mild slopes</li>
                <li><strong>Rill erosion:</strong> small channels formed by water</li>
                <li><strong>Gully erosion:</strong> deep channels; advanced stage; very damaging (Chambal ravines)</li>
                <li><strong>Wind erosion:</strong> arid regions (Thar)</li>
                <li><strong>Splash erosion:</strong> raindrop impact</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Soil conservation measures:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Mechanical:</strong> contour bunding, terracing (slopes &gt; 7°), check dams, retaining walls</li>
                <li><strong>Agronomic:</strong> contour cropping, strip cropping, mulching, cover crops</li>
                <li><strong>Biological:</strong> afforestation, agroforestry, vegetative barriers (vetiver grass)</li>
                <li><strong>Watershed management:</strong> integrated approach</li>
            </ul>
            India loses ~15.35 t/ha/yr soil to erosion (ICAR estimate); target sustainable rate &lt; 5 t/ha/yr.
        </div>

        <h3>5.5 ENERGY RESOURCES</h3>
        <div class="standard">
            <strong>India installed power capacity (2024): ~444 GW</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Coal/lignite: ~210 GW (47%)</li>
                <li>RE incl. large hydro: ~191 GW (43%); achieved 200 GW non-fossil milestone Nov 2024</li>
                <li>Solar: ~94 GW; Wind: ~47 GW; Large hydro: ~47 GW; Bioenergy: ~11 GW; Small hydro: ~5 GW</li>
                <li>Nuclear: ~8 GW (24 reactors, 8 more under construction)</li>
                <li>Gas + diesel: ~25 GW</li>
                <li><strong>Target: 500 GW non-fossil capacity by 2030</strong> (Panchamrit COP26)</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Solar mission:</strong> Jawaharlal Nehru National Solar Mission 2010; revised target 100 GW (2022) — exceeded; new target 280 GW solar by 2030. PM-KUSUM (solar pumps for farmers); Rooftop Solar; Solar Parks.<br/>
            <strong>Wind:</strong> India 4th largest globally; mostly TN, Gujarat, Karnataka, MP, Maharashtra, AP.<br/>
            <strong>Bioenergy:</strong> bagasse cogen, biomass, biogas, biofuels (E20 by 2025).<br/>
            <strong>Hydrogen:</strong> National Green Hydrogen Mission 2023 — 5 MMT/yr by 2030; ₹19,744 cr outlay.
        </div>

        <div class="gate-add">
            <strong>GATE ADD — Energy-environment nexus:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>~75% of global GHG emissions from energy sector</li>
                <li>Trade-offs: nuclear (low GHG, but waste/safety); large hydro (low GHG, but ecosystem disruption); biofuel (renewable, but land use &amp; food competition)</li>
                <li><strong>Energy intensity</strong> of GDP = energy consumed / GDP; declining in India (target −45% by 2030)</li>
                <li><strong>Levelised Cost of Electricity (LCOE)</strong> — solar PV in India: ~₹2.0–2.5/kWh (2024); coal ~₹3.5–4.5/kWh; wind ~₹2.5–3/kWh</li>
                <li><strong>Energy access:</strong> 100% village electrification (Saubhagya 2018); LPG access via PMUY</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>5.6 MINERAL RESOURCES</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <ul>
                <li>India is rich in iron ore (Goa, Jharkhand, Odisha, Karnataka), bauxite, mica, coal, limestone, manganese</li>
                <li>Imports: crude oil (~85%), natural gas (~50%), coking coal, copper</li>
                <li>"Critical minerals" list (2023, MoM): 30 minerals critical for energy transition (Li, Co, Ni, Cu, REE, graphite, tungsten)</li>
                <li>Mining environmental impacts: deforestation, soil erosion, water pollution (AMD — acid mine drainage), air pollution (PM, blasting), biodiversity loss, displacement</li>
                <li><strong>Mines &amp; Minerals (Development &amp; Regulation) Act 1957</strong> + amendments 2015, 2021, 2023</li>
                <li><strong>DMF (District Mineral Foundation)</strong> &amp; <strong>NMET (National Mineral Exploration Trust)</strong> created 2015 — funded by mining royalty</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

